    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1871-06-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1871-06-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="227"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d227">
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">No. 210.</seg>
                </opener>
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Fish</persName> to <persName type="to">General
                        Schenck</persName>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 9.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic"
                                >Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1871-06-20">
                            <hi rend="italic">June</hi> 20, 1871.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> Referring to my No. 3 of the 19th ultimo, in
                    relation to the pending negotiations of a consular convention with the British
                    government, I will thank you to propose the adoption of an article providing for
                    the administration of oaths by the consuls of either country residing in the
                    other. This you will do at such time and in such manner as may, in your
                    judgment, be most opportune and appropriate. This is especially to be desired by
                    this Government, as consuls are required, by existing Treasury regulations, to
                    see that all invoices verified by them are supported by the oath of the
                    party.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>HAMILTON FISH.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
